  "articleSummary": "The article advocates starting new feature development with a simple key-value (KV) store (e.g., Redis, S3) instead of immediately choosing SQL or MongoDB. It argues this approach speeds early development by reducing schema churn and leveraging optimized key lookups, while noting KV patterns can represent graphs and trees via key hierarchies. The tutorial-style piece provides guidance on when to use or avoid KV patterns, emphasizing that migrating from KV to SQL is easier than the reverse. The intended audience is software engineers and architects designing data persistence for new systems.",
